why it is misleading in relation to labor markets. Please also examine the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to labor markets. Another important angle is an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to labor markets. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. For practical context, discuss what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to labor markets. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to labor markets. When developing the answer, connect this to which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to labor markets. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. The response should make room for which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to labor markets. Where appropriate, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to labor markets. As part of the explanation, address how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to labor markets. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. In addition, consider the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to labor markets. A useful answer should cover the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to labor markets. To make the response more complete, include a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to labor markets. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. Please also examine how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to labor markets. Another important angle is the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to labor markets. A balanced response should mention how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to labor markets. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. To avoid oversimplifying, include what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to labor markets. When developing the answer, connect this to one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to labor markets. A reader would also benefit from understanding the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to labor markets. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. Where appropriate, include how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to labor markets. As part of the explanation, address how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to labor markets. Also include a discussion of the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to labor markets. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. A useful answer should cover what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to labor markets. To make the response more complete, include why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to labor markets. The explanation should not ignore how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to labor markets. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. Another important angle is the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to labor markets. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetiti