INFO 05-05 17:26:54 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-8af4c83eef2a428786b29bf725a94126-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about nutrition for a university student writing an introductory essay. Please compare the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. When developing the answer, connect this to the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to nutrition. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. The response should make room for the short-term effects people notice first in relation to nutrition. Where appropriate, include the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to nutrition. As part of the explanation, address why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to nutrition. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. In addition, consider how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to nutrition. A useful answer should cover how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to nutrition. To make the response more complete, include a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to nutrition. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. Please also examine what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to nutrition. Another important angle is a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to nutrition. A balanced response should mention a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to nutrition. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. To avoid oversimplifying, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to nutrition. When developing the answer, connect this to the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to nutrition. A reader would also benefit from understanding the most realistic solutions available today in relation to nutrition. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. Where appropriate, include ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to nutrition. As part of the explanation, address how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to nutrition. Also include a discussion of the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to nutrition. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. A useful answer should cover the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to nutrition. To make the response more complete, include the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to nutrition. The explanation should not ignore how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to nutrition. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. Another important angle is the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to nutrition. A balanced response should mention the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to nutrition. For practical context, discuss which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to nutrition. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. When developing the answer, connect this to how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to nutrition. A reader would also benefit from understanding how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to nutrition. The response should make room for one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to nutrition. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. As part of the explanation, address a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to nutrition. Also include a discussion of how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to nutrition. In addition, consider how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to nutrition. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. To make the response more complete, include a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to nutrition. The explanation should not ignore how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to nutrition. Please also examine the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to nutrition. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. A balanced response should mention what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to nutrition. For practical context, discuss what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to nutrition. To avoid oversimplifying, include how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to nutrition. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. A reader would also benefit from understanding the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to nutrition. The response should make room for what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to nutrition. Where appropriate, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to nutrition. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 1954, 22094, 366, 526, 10223, 292, 263, 2821, 28976, 1234, 1048, 18254, 29878, 654, 363, 263, 16372, 8368, 5007, 385, 22909, 2199, 706, 3686, 388, 29889, 3529, 7252, 278, 6964, 29892, 2020, 372, 13750, 29892, 322, 920, 2305, 881, 1348, 1048, 967, 15031, 2411, 5795, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 278, 6297, 310, 1737, 5275, 29892, 22035, 12425, 29892, 322, 2130, 304, 7788, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 319, 5405, 3763, 18028, 17099, 29936, 5649, 920, 278, 7014, 29279, 304, 1269, 916, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 278, 3273, 29899, 8489, 9545, 2305, 8369, 937, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 5837, 1887, 5855, 508, 1735, 825, 18139, 408, 263, 1781, 1650, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 2020, 970, 9311, 13750, 746, 2902, 1372, 23120, 1048, 278, 11261, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 8561, 2821, 607, 5633, 310, 278, 2228, 526, 16021, 29892, 607, 526, 17407, 29892, 322, 607, 526, 11314, 936, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 920, 278, 9545, 1163, 4822, 23507, 29892, 12786, 29892, 470, 17869, 6471, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 319, 5407, 1234, 881, 4612, 920, 278, 2228, 6602, 29879, 15311, 14218, 2834, 3265, 1135, 871, 2902, 1372, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 1763, 1207, 278, 2933, 901, 4866, 29892, 3160, 263, 10230, 1546, 1023, 1422, 13501, 304, 278, 1021, 18766, 297, 8220, 304, 18254, 29878, 654, 29889, 6652, 6202