INFO 05-05 17:27:25 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-cb355b7093e14f2b81793deacac5259d-0: prompt: 'I am trying to understand sustainable cities from the perspective of a journalist planning background research for an explainer article. Please clarify the topic in a way that is accurate, accessible, and useful for decision making. Where appropriate, include the most realistic solutions available today in relation to sustainable cities. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. Also include a discussion of an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to sustainable cities. In addition, consider the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to sustainable cities. A useful answer should cover the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to sustainable cities. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. The explanation should not ignore ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to sustainable cities. Please also examine the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to sustainable cities. Another important angle is a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to sustainable cities. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. For practical context, discuss a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to sustainable cities. To avoid oversimplifying, include how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to sustainable cities. When developing the answer, connect this to why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to sustainable cities. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. The response should make room for how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to sustainable cities. Where appropriate, include how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to sustainable cities. As part of the explanation, address how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to sustainable cities. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. In addition, consider how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to sustainable cities. A useful answer should cover how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to sustainable cities. To make the response more complete, include the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to sustainable cities. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. Please also examine the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to sustainable cities. Another important angle is how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to sustainable cities. A balanced response should mention what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to sustainable cities. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. To avoid oversimplifying, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to sustainable cities. When developing the answer, connect this to how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to sustainable cities. A reader would also benefit from understanding what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to sustainable cities. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. Where appropriate, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to sustainable cities. As part of the explanation, address one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to sustainable cities. Also include a discussion of the short-term effects people notice first in relation to sustainable cities. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. A useful answer should cover the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to sustainable cities. To make the response more complete, include the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to sustainable cities. The explanation should not ignore the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to sustainable cities. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. Another important angle is which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to sustainable cities. A balanced response should mention what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to sustainable cities. For practical context, discuss the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to sustainable cities. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. When developing the answer, connect this to the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to sustainable cities. A reader would also benefit from understanding the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to sustainable cities. The response should make room for how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to sustainable cities. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. As part of the explanation, address what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to sustainable cities. Please emphasize clarity, accuracy, and balanced reasoning throughout the response.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 306, 626, 1811, 304, 2274, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 515, 278, 18520, 310, 263, 24452, 18987, 3239, 5925, 363, 385, 3641, 4983, 4274, 29889, 3529, 15544, 278, 11261, 297, 263, 982, 393, 338, 16232, 29892, 15579, 29892, 322, 5407, 363, 10608, 3907, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 1556, 1855, 4695, 6851, 3625, 9826, 297, 8220, 304, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 29889, 8561, 2821, 607, 5633, 310, 278, 2228, 526, 16021, 29892, 607, 526, 17407, 29892, 322, 607, 526, 11314, 936, 29889, 3115, 3160, 263, 10679, 310, 385, 1342, 393, 4511, 29879, 278, 11261, 304, 10466, 29892, 7766, 1199, 29892, 322, 970, 8898, 297, 8220, 304, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 278, 5837, 1887, 5855, 508, 1735, 825, 18139, 408, 263, 1781, 1650, 297, 8220, 304, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 29889, 319, 5407, 1234, 881, 4612, 278, 11302, 22450, 1546, 6210, 29892, 6534, 2264, 29892, 21750, 3097, 29892, 322, 1472, 29899, 8489, 1411, 3097, 297, 8220, 304, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 29889, 8561, 278, 2933, 5407, 363, 4856, 1058, 4225, 1716, 3239, 7134, 322, 15031, 24284, 29889, 450, 8252, 881, 451, 11455, 11314, 936, 5155, 393, 2615, 2748, 278, 11261, 338, 7436, 297, 6944, 297, 8220, 304, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 29889, 3529, 884, 25917, 278, 16905, 11938, 393, 1207, 2560, 6851, 5189, 297, 8220, 304, 15075, 475, 519, 14368, 29889, 7280, 4100, 10696, 338, 263, 10483, 6445, 920, 278, 11261, 1795, 4383, 297, 278, 2446, 316, 6332, 297, 8220, 304, 