INFO 05-05 17:27:56 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-d91aac7a750b47d282206ef74666e4fd-0: prompt: 'Provide a thoughtful explanation of genetics for a policymaker looking for practical implications rather than slogans. The goal is not just to define the term, but to show how the topic works in real situations. In addition, consider the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to genetics. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. To make the response more complete, include a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to genetics. The explanation should not ignore how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to genetics. Please also examine the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to genetics. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. A balanced response should mention the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to genetics. For practical context, discuss a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to genetics. To avoid oversimplifying, include the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to genetics. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to genetics. The response should make room for the main causes that created the current situation in relation to genetics. Where appropriate, include how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to genetics. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Also include a discussion of the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to genetics. In addition, consider a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to genetics. A useful answer should cover how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to genetics. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. The explanation should not ignore the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to genetics. Please also examine how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to genetics. Another important angle is the most realistic solutions available today in relation to genetics. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. For practical context, discuss how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to genetics. To avoid oversimplifying, include a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to genetics. When developing the answer, connect this to what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to genetics. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. The response should make room for the short-term effects people notice first in relation to genetics. Where appropriate, include how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to genetics. As part of the explanation, address an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to genetics. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. In addition, consider how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to genetics. A useful answer should cover the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to genetics. To make the response more complete, include the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to genetics. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. Please also examine the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to genetics. Another important angle is how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to genetics. A balanced response should mention how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to genetics. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. To avoid oversimplifying, include the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to genetics. When developing the answer, connect this to what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to genetics. A reader would also benefit from understanding which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to genetics. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. Where appropriate, include a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to genetics. As part of the explanation, address an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to genetics. Also include a discussion of one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to genetics. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. A useful answer should cover the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to genetics. To make the response more complete, include which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to genetics. The explanation should not ignore how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to genetics. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. Avoid unsupported claims and make the reasoning easy to follow.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, 