INFO 05-05 17:28:17 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-87e1f09026054891baad91d7e17e2709-0: prompt: 'I am trying to understand epidemiology from the perspective of a parent trying to explain the idea to a teenager. Please compare the topic in a way that is accurate, accessible, and useful for decision making. To make the response more complete, include how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to epidemiology. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. Please also examine an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to epidemiology. Another important angle is how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to epidemiology. A balanced response should mention which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to epidemiology. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. To avoid oversimplifying, include how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to epidemiology. When developing the answer, connect this to how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to epidemiology. A reader would also benefit from understanding what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to epidemiology. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. Where appropriate, include how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to epidemiology. As part of the explanation, address an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to epidemiology. Also include a discussion of the most realistic solutions available today in relation to epidemiology. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. A useful answer should cover ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to epidemiology. To make the response more complete, include how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to epidemiology. The explanation should not ignore the main causes that created the current situation in relation to epidemiology. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. Another important angle is a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to epidemiology. A balanced response should mention how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to epidemiology. For practical context, discuss the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to epidemiology. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. When developing the answer, connect this to one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to epidemiology. A reader would also benefit from understanding the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to epidemiology. The response should make room for what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to epidemiology. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. As part of the explanation, address the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to epidemiology. Also include a discussion of how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to epidemiology. In addition, consider how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to epidemiology. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. To make the response more complete, include what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to epidemiology. The explanation should not ignore the short-term effects people notice first in relation to epidemiology. Please also examine the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to epidemiology. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. A balanced response should mention the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to epidemiology. For practical context, discuss a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to epidemiology. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to epidemiology. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. A reader would also benefit from understanding a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to epidemiology. The response should make room for how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to epidemiology. Where appropriate, include how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to epidemiology. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. Also include a discussion of the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to epidemiology. In addition, consider how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to epidemiology. A useful answer should cover how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to epidemiology. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. The explanation should not ignore the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to epidemiology. Please also examine the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to epidemiology. Another important angle is what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to epidemiology. Please emphasize clar