anced response should mention a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to financial literacy. For practical context, discuss how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to financial literacy. To avoid oversimplifying, include the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to financial literacy. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. A reader would also benefit from understanding what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to financial literacy. The response should make room for the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to financial literacy. Where appropriate, include how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to financial literacy. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. Also include a discussion of how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to financial literacy. In addition, consider how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to financial literacy. A useful answer should cover what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to financial literacy. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. The explanation should not ignore an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to financial literacy. Please also examine a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to financial literacy. Another important angle is a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to financial literacy. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. For practical context, discuss how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to financial literacy. To avoid oversimplifying, include how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to financial literacy. When developing the answer, connect this to the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to financial literacy. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. The response should make room for what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to financial literacy. Where appropriate, include the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to financial literacy. As part of the explanation, address why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to financial literacy. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. In addition, consider how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to financial literacy. A useful answer should cover the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to financial literacy. To make the response more complete, include the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to financial literacy. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. Please also examine how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to financial literacy. Another important angle is ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to financial literacy. A balanced response should mention a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to financial literacy. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. To avoid oversimplifying, include one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to financial literacy. Please emphasize clarity, accuracy, and balanced reasoning throughout the response.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 306, 626, 1811, 304, 2274, 18161, 4631, 4135, 515, 278, 18520, 310, 263, 1661, 771, 9202, 27886, 261, 17420, 1950, 1006, 794, 1080, 29889, 3529, 14707, 278, 11261, 297, 263, 982, 393, 338, 16232, 29892, 15579, 29892, 322, 5407, 363, 10608, 3907, 29889, 1152, 15031, 3030, 29892, 5353, 278, 3273, 29899, 8489, 9545, 2305, 8369, 937, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 1938, 451, 2436, 263, 1423, 1761, 29936, 7738, 263, 16165, 261, 296, 7309, 7606, 1234, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 920, 25812, 881, 367, 16459, 746, 10757, 338, 28907, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 920, 278, 11261, 1033, 6602, 2305, 17587, 8679, 373, 5046, 29892, 17869, 29892, 4423, 29892, 470, 9793, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 278, 1667, 9946, 393, 2825, 278, 1857, 6434, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 20355, 915, 920, 278, 11261, 4511, 29879, 304, 1432, 3250, 2834, 408, 1532, 408, 7200, 5264, 6757, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 278, 1556, 1855, 4695, 6851, 3625, 9826, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 3115, 3160, 263, 10679, 310, 278, 6297, 310, 1737, 5275, 29892, 22035, 12425, 29892, 322, 2130, 304, 7788, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 920, 278, 9545, 1163, 4822, 23507, 29892, 12786, 29892, 470, 17869, 6471, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 12027, 7420, 278, 4328, 1546, 19869, 29