INFO 05-05 17:30:11 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-d0a10b33aaf74b10a4e79d4358b264d3-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about human memory for a parent trying to explain the idea to a teenager. Please compare the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. Also include a discussion of how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to human memory. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. A useful answer should cover how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to human memory. To make the response more complete, include an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to human memory. The explanation should not ignore how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to human memory. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. Another important angle is which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to human memory. A balanced response should mention the most realistic solutions available today in relation to human memory. For practical context, discuss the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to human memory. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. When developing the answer, connect this to the main causes that created the current situation in relation to human memory. A reader would also benefit from understanding the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to human memory. The response should make room for how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to human memory. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. As part of the explanation, address the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to human memory. Also include a discussion of what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to human memory. In addition, consider how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to human memory. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. To make the response more complete, include a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to human memory. The explanation should not ignore the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to human memory. Please also examine the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to human memory. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. A balanced response should mention the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to human memory. For practical context, discuss what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to human memory. To avoid oversimplifying, include the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to human memory. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. A reader would also benefit from understanding how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to human memory. The response should make room for a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to human memory. Where appropriate, include how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to human memory. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. Also include a discussion of a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to human memory. In addition, consider the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to human memory. A useful answer should cover what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to human memory. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. The explanation should not ignore a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to human memory. Please also examine ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to human memory. Another important angle is how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to human memory. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. For practical context, discuss how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to human memory. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to human memory. When developing the answer, connect this to the short-term effects people notice first in relation to human memory. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. The response should make room for the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to human memory. Where appropriate, include a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to human memory. As part of the explanation, address an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to human memory. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. In addition, consider how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to human memory. A useful answer should cover the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to human memory. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParam