INFO 05-05 17:31:56 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-9f2f71999f264c4cbfdea68571d3bd8a-0: prompt: 'Provide a thoughtful explanation of biodiversity for a curious adult with no technical background. The goal is not just to define the term, but to show how the topic works in real situations. A reader would also benefit from understanding a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to biodiversity. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. Where appropriate, include the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to biodiversity. As part of the explanation, address ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to biodiversity. Also include a discussion of how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to biodiversity. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. A useful answer should cover what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to biodiversity. To make the response more complete, include how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to biodiversity. The explanation should not ignore the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to biodiversity. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. Another important angle is the most realistic solutions available today in relation to biodiversity. A balanced response should mention the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to biodiversity. For practical context, discuss a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to biodiversity. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. When developing the answer, connect this to the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to biodiversity. A reader would also benefit from understanding how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to biodiversity. The response should make room for a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to biodiversity. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. As part of the explanation, address which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to biodiversity. Also include a discussion of how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to biodiversity. In addition, consider an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to biodiversity. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. To make the response more complete, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to biodiversity. The explanation should not ignore how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to biodiversity. Please also examine what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to biodiversity. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. A balanced response should mention the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to biodiversity. For practical context, discuss what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to biodiversity. To avoid oversimplifying, include one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to biodiversity. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. A reader would also benefit from understanding the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to biodiversity. The response should make room for the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to biodiversity. Where appropriate, include how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to biodiversity. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. Also include a discussion of how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to biodiversity. In addition, consider how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to biodiversity. A useful answer should cover what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to biodiversity. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. The explanation should not ignore the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to biodiversity. Please also examine the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to biodiversity. Another important angle is how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to biodiversity. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. For practical context, discuss the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to biodiversity. To avoid oversimplifying, include an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to biodiversity. When developing the answer, connect this to what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to biodiversity. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. The response should make room for how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to biodiversity. Where appropriate, include the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to biodiversity. As part of the explanation, address how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to biodiversity. Avoid unsupported claims and make the reasoning easy to follow.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 9133, 680, 263, 2714, 1319, 8252, 310, 289, 2660, 24974, 363, 263, 12758, 16157, 411, 694, 16905, 3239, 29889, 450, 7306, 338, 451, 925, 304, 4529, 278, 1840, 29892, 541, 304, 1510, 920, 278, 11261, 1736, 297, 1855, 18845, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 263, 10230, 1546, 1023, 1422, 13501, 304, 278, 1021, 18766, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 6804, 5407, 29892, 7252, 5375, 8820, 411, 12666, 284, 470, 1788, 29899, 5563, 3620, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 15839, 2693, 1860, 393, 1754, 278, 2228, 901, 4100, 975, 931, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 11314, 936, 5155, 393, 2615, 2748, 278, 11261, 338, 7436, 297, 6944, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 3115, 3160, 263, 10679, 310, 920, 304, 1207, 278, 8252, 5407, 304, 4856, 1058, 1818, 1207, 263, 10608, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 319, 5405, 3763, 18028, 17099, 29936, 5649, 920, 278, 7014, 29279, 304, 1269, 916, 29889, 319, 5407, 1234, 881, 4612, 825, 2472, 723, 367, 1556, 4100, 297, 263, 3273, 24329, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 1763, 1207, 278, 2933, 901, 4866, 29892, 3160, 920, 278, 11261, 1795, 1106, 1422, 297, 17173, 29891, 322, 4482, 29899, 10314, 6055, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 450, 8252, 881, 451, 11455, 278, 29380, 29892, 5264, 29892, 322, 17407, 18563, 5742, 278, 1108, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 319, 5405, 3907, 278, 2933, 883