INFO 05-05 17:32:06 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-ab1e24842e594ad1917591539550410c-0: prompt: 'I need a well-organized answer about language learning. Assume the reader is a parent trying to explain the idea to a teenager, and focus on clarity, examples, tradeoffs, and common misunderstandings. The response should make room for ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to language learning. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. As part of the explanation, address what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to language learning. Also include a discussion of the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to language learning. In addition, consider how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to language learning. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. To make the response more complete, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to language learning. The explanation should not ignore one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to language learning. Please also examine how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to language learning. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. A balanced response should mention which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to language learning. For practical context, discuss a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to language learning. To avoid oversimplifying, include how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to language learning. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. A reader would also benefit from understanding the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to language learning. The response should make room for what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to language learning. Where appropriate, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to language learning. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. Also include a discussion of what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to language learning. In addition, consider how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to language learning. A useful answer should cover the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to language learning. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. The explanation should not ignore a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to language learning. Please also examine the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to language learning. Another important angle is the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to language learning. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. For practical context, discuss the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to language learning. To avoid oversimplifying, include why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to language learning. When developing the answer, connect this to the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to language learning. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. The response should make room for how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to language learning. Where appropriate, include a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to language learning. As part of the explanation, address the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to language learning. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. In addition, consider the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to language learning. A useful answer should cover the most realistic solutions available today in relation to language learning. To make the response more complete, include the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to language learning. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. Please also examine how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to language learning. Another important angle is how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to language learning. A balanced response should mention how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to language learning. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. To avoid oversimplifying, include a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to language learning. When developing the answer, connect this to the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to language learning. A reader would also benefit from understanding a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to language learning. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. Where appropriate, include how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to language learning. The answer should be useful as backgrou