INFO 05-05 17:32:29 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-ea99dd6cd60041988a95a6534bc38bf2-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about democracy for a museum educator designing an accessible exhibit. Please clarify the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. Also include a discussion of the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to democracy. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. A useful answer should cover how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to democracy. To make the response more complete, include the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to democracy. The explanation should not ignore the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to democracy. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. Another important angle is how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to democracy. A balanced response should mention a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to democracy. For practical context, discuss why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to democracy. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. When developing the answer, connect this to how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to democracy. A reader would also benefit from understanding the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to democracy. The response should make room for how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to democracy. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. As part of the explanation, address how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to democracy. Also include a discussion of which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to democracy. In addition, consider an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to democracy. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. To make the response more complete, include a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to democracy. The explanation should not ignore the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to democracy. Please also examine the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to democracy. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. A balanced response should mention the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to democracy. For practical context, discuss how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to democracy. To avoid oversimplifying, include what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to democracy. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. A reader would also benefit from understanding how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to democracy. The response should make room for the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to democracy. Where appropriate, include how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to democracy. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Also include a discussion of the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to democracy. In addition, consider what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to democracy. A useful answer should cover the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to democracy. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. The explanation should not ignore ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to democracy. Please also examine what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to democracy. Another important angle is one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to democracy. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. For practical context, discuss a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to democracy. To avoid oversimplifying, include how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to democracy. When developing the answer, connect this to the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to democracy. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. The response should make room for a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to democracy. Where appropriate, include what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to democracy. As part of the explanation, address the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to democracy. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. In addition, consider what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to democracy. A useful answer should cover how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to democracy. To make the response more complete, include a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to democracy. The final response shoul