INFO 05-05 17:33:42 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-192fb1caa94941cd91e19cc5c84dba14-0: prompt: 'I am trying to understand behavioral economics from the perspective of a curious adult with no technical background. Please clarify the topic in a way that is accurate, accessible, and useful for decision making. For practical context, discuss the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to behavioral economics. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. When developing the answer, connect this to a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to behavioral economics. A reader would also benefit from understanding how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to behavioral economics. The response should make room for what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to behavioral economics. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. As part of the explanation, address what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to behavioral economics. Also include a discussion of how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to behavioral economics. In addition, consider ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to behavioral economics. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. To make the response more complete, include a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to behavioral economics. The explanation should not ignore the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to behavioral economics. Please also examine why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to behavioral economics. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. A balanced response should mention how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to behavioral economics. For practical context, discuss the short-term effects people notice first in relation to behavioral economics. To avoid oversimplifying, include the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to behavioral economics. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to behavioral economics. The response should make room for how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to behavioral economics. Where appropriate, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to behavioral economics. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. Also include a discussion of which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to behavioral economics. In addition, consider the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to behavioral economics. A useful answer should cover how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to behavioral economics. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. The explanation should not ignore the most realistic solutions available today in relation to behavioral economics. Please also examine how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to behavioral economics. Another important angle is which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to behavioral economics. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. For practical context, discuss the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to behavioral economics. To avoid oversimplifying, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to behavioral economics. When developing the answer, connect this to how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to behavioral economics. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. The response should make room for what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to behavioral economics. Where appropriate, include an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to behavioral economics. As part of the explanation, address the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to behavioral economics. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. In addition, consider one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to behavioral economics. A useful answer should cover what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to behavioral economics. To make the response more complete, include how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to behavioral economics. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Please also examine how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to behavioral economics. Another important angle is the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to behavioral economics. A balanced response should mention the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to behavioral economics. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to behavioral economics. When developing the answer, connect this to the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to behavioral economics. Please emphasize clarity, accuracy, and balanced reasoning throughout the response.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 306, 626, 1811, 304, 2274, 6030, 284, 7766, 1199, 515, 278, 18520, 310, 263, 12758, 16157, 411, 694, 16905, 3239, 29889, 3529, 15544, 278, 11261, 297, 263, 982, 393, 338, 16232, 29892, 15579, 29892, 322, 5407, 363, 10608, 3907, 29889, 1152, 15031, 3030, 29892, 5353, 278, 5161, 2039, 310, 5330, 8253, 278, 2228, 2745, 372, 7415, 901, 19390, 304, 3211, 297, 8220, 304, 6030, 284, 7766, 1199, 29889, 1938, 451, 2436, 263, 1423, 1761, 29936, 7738, 263, 16165, 261, 296, 7309, 7606, 1234, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 263, 1855, 29899, 11526, 3483, 6933, 393, 947, 451, 288, 874, 13699, 1598, 278, 2228, 297, 8220, 304, 6030, 284, 7766, 1199, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 920, 848, 11029, 508, 8267, 278, 12536, 3097, 310, 21204, 1080, 297, 8220, 304, 6030, 284, 7766, 1199, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 825, 263, 26605, 338, 1556, 5517, 304, 19818, 1689, 472, 937, 297, 8220, 304, 6030, 284, 7766, 1199, 29889, 6652, 6202, 728, 1546, 3273, 29899, 8489, 15031, 537, 322, 1472, 29899, 8489, 15075, 475, 3097, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 825, 5155, 263, 18109, 415, 936, 20026, 723, 3117, 2244, 297, 8220, 304, 6030, 284, 7766, 1199, 29889, 3115, 3160, 263, 10679, 310, 920, 21544, 322, 23633, 1122, 1735, 408, 278, 1650, 338, 6287, 29881, 701, 297, 8220, 304, 