INFO 05-05 17:34:03 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-a8d2a402955c4028abd1de6eb7fe41a2-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about labor markets for a high school student preparing for a class discussion. Please evaluate the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. When developing the answer, connect this to how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to labor markets. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. The response should make room for how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to labor markets. Where appropriate, include how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to labor markets. As part of the explanation, address the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to labor markets. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. In addition, consider how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to labor markets. A useful answer should cover the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to labor markets. To make the response more complete, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to labor markets. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. Please also examine how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to labor markets. Another important angle is the main causes that created the current situation in relation to labor markets. A balanced response should mention which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to labor markets. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. To avoid oversimplifying, include the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to labor markets. When developing the answer, connect this to a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to labor markets. A reader would also benefit from understanding a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to labor markets. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. Where appropriate, include what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to labor markets. As part of the explanation, address what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to labor markets. Also include a discussion of a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to labor markets. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. A useful answer should cover a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to labor markets. To make the response more complete, include an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to labor markets. The explanation should not ignore what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to labor markets. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. Another important angle is the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to labor markets. A balanced response should mention the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to labor markets. For practical context, discuss what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to labor markets. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. When developing the answer, connect this to the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to labor markets. A reader would also benefit from understanding how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to labor markets. The response should make room for how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to labor markets. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. As part of the explanation, address the most realistic solutions available today in relation to labor markets. Also include a discussion of which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to labor markets. In addition, consider how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to labor markets. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. To make the response more complete, include ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to labor markets. The explanation should not ignore how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to labor markets. Please also examine the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to labor markets. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. A balanced response should mention an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to labor markets. For practical context, discuss the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to labor markets. To avoid oversimplifying, include the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to labor markets. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.