ear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to urban planning. As part of the explanation, address how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to urban planning. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. In addition, consider a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to urban planning. A useful answer should cover the main causes that created the current situation in relation to urban planning. To make the response more complete, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to urban planning. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. Please also examine the most realistic solutions available today in relation to urban planning. Another important angle is the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to urban planning. A balanced response should mention the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to urban planning. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. To avoid oversimplifying, include what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to urban planning. When developing the answer, connect this to how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to urban planning. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to urban planning. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. Where appropriate, include how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to urban planning. As part of the explanation, address a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to urban planning. The answer should be useful as background for a classroom discussion or short written report.'