INFO 05-05 17:34:34 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-38d8b98b1814435b80bda8e21036f3ac-0: prompt: 'I am trying to understand food systems from the perspective of a university student writing an introductory essay. Please compare the topic in a way that is accurate, accessible, and useful for decision making. Where appropriate, include how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to food systems. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. Also include a discussion of a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to food systems. In addition, consider what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to food systems. A useful answer should cover the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to food systems. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. The explanation should not ignore what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to food systems. Please also examine the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to food systems. Another important angle is what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to food systems. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. For practical context, discuss the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to food systems. To avoid oversimplifying, include how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to food systems. When developing the answer, connect this to how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to food systems. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. The response should make room for an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to food systems. Where appropriate, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to food systems. As part of the explanation, address how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to food systems. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. In addition, consider how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to food systems. A useful answer should cover how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to food systems. To make the response more complete, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to food systems. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Please also examine how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to food systems. Another important angle is the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to food systems. A balanced response should mention one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to food systems. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to food systems. When developing the answer, connect this to a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to food systems. A reader would also benefit from understanding the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to food systems. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. Where appropriate, include how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to food systems. As part of the explanation, address the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to food systems. Also include a discussion of a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to food systems. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. A useful answer should cover how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to food systems. To make the response more complete, include the short-term effects people notice first in relation to food systems. The explanation should not ignore an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to food systems. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. Another important angle is how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to food systems. A balanced response should mention the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to food systems. For practical context, discuss the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to food systems. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. When developing the answer, connect this to the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to food systems. A reader would also benefit from understanding how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to food systems. The response should make room for how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to food systems. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. As part of the explanation, address the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to food systems. Also include a discussion of the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to food systems. Please emphasize clarity, accuracy, and balanced reasoning throughout the response.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0