INFO 05-05 17:35:22 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-92240aa416ef433989a825726f698a1c-0: prompt: 'Write a general-knowledge explanation about renewable energy for a policymaker looking for practical implications rather than slogans. The response should be self-contained and should help the reader understand both the basic idea and its broader importance. The explanation should not ignore the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to renewable energy. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. Another important angle is the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to renewable energy. A balanced response should mention the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to renewable energy. For practical context, discuss how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to renewable energy. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. When developing the answer, connect this to how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to renewable energy. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to renewable energy. The response should make room for how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to renewable energy. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. As part of the explanation, address what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to renewable energy. Also include a discussion of why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to renewable energy. In addition, consider the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to renewable energy. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. To make the response more complete, include how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to renewable energy. The explanation should not ignore what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to renewable energy. Please also examine a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to renewable energy. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. A balanced response should mention the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to renewable energy. For practical context, discuss how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to renewable energy. To avoid oversimplifying, include how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to renewable energy. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. A reader would also benefit from understanding how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to renewable energy. The response should make room for how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to renewable energy. Where appropriate, include which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to renewable energy. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Also include a discussion of the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to renewable energy. In addition, consider an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to renewable energy. A useful answer should cover a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to renewable energy. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. The explanation should not ignore the main causes that created the current situation in relation to renewable energy. Please also examine the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to renewable energy. Another important angle is the most realistic solutions available today in relation to renewable energy. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. For practical context, discuss one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to renewable energy. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to renewable energy. When developing the answer, connect this to the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to renewable energy. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. The response should make room for a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to renewable energy. Where appropriate, include which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to renewable energy. As part of the explanation, address an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to renewable energy. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. In addition, consider what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to renewable energy. A useful answer should cover the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to renewable energy. To make the response more complete, include the short-term effects people notice first in relation to renewable energy. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. Please also examine the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to renewable energy. Another important angle is the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to renewable energy. Please keep the answer focused on explanation rather than persuasion.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 14350, 263, 2498, 29899, 28385, 5485, 8252, 1048, 23011, 519, 5864, 363, 263, 13665, 962, 5790, 3063, 363, 15031, 2411, 5795, 3265, 1135, 269, 1188, 550, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 367, 1583, 29899, 1285, 7114, 322, 881, 1371, 278, 9591, 2274, 1716, 278, 6996, 2969, 322, 967, 2545, 1664, 13500, 29889, 450, 8252, 881, 451, 11455, 278, 297, 1760, 3145, 393, 8267, 920, 2305, 322, 21561, 23389, 297, 8220, 304, 23011, 519, 5864, 29889, 12027, 7420, 278, 4328, 1546, 19869, 29892, 3269, 362, 29892, 322, 15590, 27262, 746, 8018, 29889, 7280, 4100, 10696, 338, 278, 15839, 2693, 1860, 393, 1754, 278, 2228, 901, 4100, 975, 931, 297, 8220, 304, 23011, 519, 5864, 29889, 319, 6411, 8362, 2933, 881, 3585, 278, 443, 524, 2760, 27721, 393, 508, 2615, 746, 263, 1650, 338, 6460, 368, 8688, 297, 8220, 304, 23011, 519, 5864, 29889, 1152, 15031, 3030, 29892, 5353, 920, 304, 20820, 17924, 1136, 8841, 515, 1722, 27836, 297, 8220, 304, 23011, 519, 5864, 29889, 960, 2999, 1776, 9748, 1863, 29892, 2755, 278, 4549, 342, 1873, 310, 1269, 1434, 6161, 1218, 963, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 920, 278, 11261, 1795, 1106, 1422, 297, 17173, 29891, 322, 4482, 29899, 10314, 6055, 297, 8220, 304, 23011, 519, 5864, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 920, 304, 1207, 278, 8252, 5407, 304, 4856, 1058, 1818, 1207, 263, 10608, 297, 8220, 304, 23011, 519, 5864, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 12