should not ignore the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to education policy. Please also examine the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to education policy. Another important angle is a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to education policy. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. For practical context, discuss a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to education policy. To avoid oversimplifying, include how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to education policy. When developing the answer, connect this to what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to education policy. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. The response should make room for the short-term effects people notice first in relation to education policy. Where appropriate, include how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to education policy. As part of the explanation, address why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to education policy. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. In addition, consider how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to education policy. A useful answer should cover the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to education policy. To make the response more complete, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to education policy. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Please also examine how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to education policy. Another important angle is how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to education policy. A balanced response should mention how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to education policy. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. To avoid oversimplifying, include ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to education policy. When developing the answer, connect this to which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to education policy. A reader would also benefit from understanding the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to education policy. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. Where appropriate, include how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to education policy. As part of the explanation, address the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to education policy. Also include a discussion of the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to education policy. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. A useful answer should cover a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to education policy. To make the response more complete, include how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to education policy. The explanation should not ignore what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to education policy. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. Another important angle is the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to education policy. A balanced response should mention what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to education policy. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 1954, 22094, 366, 526, 10223, 292, 263, 2821, 28976, 1234, 1048, 9793, 8898, 363, 263, 12758, 16157, 411, 694, 16905, 3239, 29889, 3529, 15544, 278, 6964, 29892, 2020, 372, 13750, 29892, 322, 920, 2305, 881, 1348, 1048, 967, 15031, 2411, 5795, 29889, 3529, 884, 25917, 920, 278, 11261, 1033, 6602, 2305, 17587, 8679, 373, 5046, 29892, 17869, 29892, 4423, 29892, 470, 9793, 297, 8220, 304, 9793, 8898, 29889, 4803, 6455, 16112, 322, 5649, 2020, 1269, 1342, 11286, 278, 2545, 1664, 1298, 29889, 319, 6411, 8362, 2933, 881, 3585, 385, 1342, 393, 4511, 29879, 278, 11261, 304, 10466, 29892, 7766, 1199, 29892, 322, 970, 8898, 297, 8220, 304, 9793, 8898, 29889, 1152, 15031, 3030, 29892, 5353, 920, 278, 2228, 6602, 29879, 15311, 14218, 2834, 3265, 1135, 871, 2902, 1372, 297, 8220, 304, 9793, 8898, 29889, 1763, 4772, 288, 874, 13699, 9215, 29892, 3160, 278, 4328, 1546, 825, 5925, 414, 1073, 322, 825, 13665, 962, 21079, 508, 2334, 297, 8220, 304, 9793, 8898, 29889, 6652, 6202, 728, 1546, 3273, 29899, 8489, 15031, 537, 322, 1472, 29899, 8489, 15075, 475, 3097, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 825, 263, 26605, 338, 1556, 5517, 304, 19818, 1689, 472, 937, 297, 8220, 304, 9793, 8898, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 385, 1342, 310, 263, 3619, 3984, 535, 1441, 322, 2020, 372, 338, 3984, 25369, 297, 8220, 304, 9793, 8898, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 5837, 1887, 5855, 508, 1735, 825, 18139, 408, 263, 1781, 1650, 