INFO 05-05 17:36:25 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-ee3e19cae8bc487d8fe89b0783adc765-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about history of medicine for a university student writing an introductory essay. Please compare the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. When developing the answer, connect this to the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to history of medicine. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. The response should make room for one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to history of medicine. Where appropriate, include the most realistic solutions available today in relation to history of medicine. As part of the explanation, address an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to history of medicine. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. In addition, consider the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to history of medicine. A useful answer should cover how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to history of medicine. To make the response more complete, include how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to history of medicine. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. Please also examine what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to history of medicine. Another important angle is which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to history of medicine. A balanced response should mention the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to history of medicine. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. To avoid oversimplifying, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to history of medicine. When developing the answer, connect this to the short-term effects people notice first in relation to history of medicine. A reader would also benefit from understanding a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to history of medicine. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. Where appropriate, include the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to history of medicine. As part of the explanation, address what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to history of medicine. Also include a discussion of a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to history of medicine. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. A useful answer should cover how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to history of medicine. To make the response more complete, include what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to history of medicine. The explanation should not ignore how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to history of medicine. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. Another important angle is a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to history of medicine. A balanced response should mention how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to history of medicine. For practical context, discuss the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to history of medicine. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. When developing the answer, connect this to what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to history of medicine. A reader would also benefit from understanding how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to history of medicine. The response should make room for how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to history of medicine. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. As part of the explanation, address the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to history of medicine. Also include a discussion of the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to history of medicine. In addition, consider the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to history of medicine. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. To make the response more complete, include a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to history of medicine. The explanation should not ignore the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to history of medicine. Please also examine what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to history of medicine. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. A balanced response should mention the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to history of medicine. For practical context, discuss the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to history of medicine. To avoid oversimplifying, include the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to history of medicine. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 1954, 22094, 366, 526, 10223, 292, 263, 2821, 28976, 1234, 1048, 4955, 310, 26602, 363, 263, 16372, 8368, 5007, 385, 22909, 2199, 706, 3686, 388, 29889, 3529, 7252, 278, 6964, 29892, 2020, 372, 13750, 29892, 322, 920, 2305, 881, 1348, 1048, 967, 15031, 2411, 5795, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 278, 11302, 22450, 1546, 6210, 29892, 6534, 2264, 29892, 21750, 3097, 29892, 322, 1472, 29899, 8489, 1411, 3097, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 319, 5405, 3763, 18028, 17099, 29936, 5649, 920, 278, 7014, 29279, 304, 1269, 916, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 697, 18387, 1342, 393, 3732, 278, 6964, 6775, 304, 2274, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 1556, 1855, 4695, 6851, 3625, 9826, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 385, 1342, 310, 263, 3619, 3984, 535, 1441, 322, 2020, 372, 338, 3984, 25369, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 1938, 451, 2436, 263, 1423, 1761, 29936, 7738, 263, 16165, 261, 296, 7309, 7606, 1234, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 278, 16905, 11938, 393, 1207, 2560, 6851, 5189, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 319, 5407, 1234, 881, 4612, 920, 304, 5649, 278, 11261, 1728, 337, 5890, 373, 432, 1191, 265, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 1763, 1207, 278, 2933, 901, 4866, 29892, 3160, 920, 2024, 19995, 16254, 411, 970, 22035, 12425, 297, 8220, 304, 4955, 310, 26602, 29889, 512, 2325, 3307, 3030, 577, 278, 1234, 3732, 4060, 304, 4856, 11735, 292, 278, 11261, 363, 278, 937, 931, 29889, 3529, 884, 25917, 825, 2472, 723, 367, 1556, 