INFO 05-05 17:36:56 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-09d995030843427da678bb12d5885ab2-0: prompt: 'I am trying to understand financial literacy from the perspective of a journalist planning background research for an explainer article. Please clarify the topic in a way that is accurate, accessible, and useful for decision making. Where appropriate, include the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to financial literacy. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. Also include a discussion of the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to financial literacy. In addition, consider the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to financial literacy. A useful answer should cover the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to financial literacy. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. The explanation should not ignore the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to financial literacy. Please also examine how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to financial literacy. Another important angle is how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to financial literacy. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. For practical context, discuss a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to financial literacy. To avoid oversimplifying, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to financial literacy. When developing the answer, connect this to how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to financial literacy. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. The response should make room for how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to financial literacy. Where appropriate, include the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to financial literacy. As part of the explanation, address one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to financial literacy. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. In addition, consider what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to financial literacy. A useful answer should cover the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to financial literacy. To make the response more complete, include how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to financial literacy. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. Please also examine a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to financial literacy. Another important angle is a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to financial literacy. A balanced response should mention the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to financial literacy. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to financial literacy. When developing the answer, connect this to what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to financial literacy. A reader would also benefit from understanding the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to financial literacy. Be explicit about any assumptions used in the explanation. Where appropriate, include how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to financial literacy. As part of the explanation, address how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to financial literacy. Also include a discussion of how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to financial literacy. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. A useful answer should cover how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to financial literacy. To make the response more complete, include a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to financial literacy. The explanation should not ignore what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to financial literacy. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. Another important angle is how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to financial literacy. A balanced response should mention the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to financial literacy. For practical context, discuss the short-term effects people notice first in relation to financial literacy. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. When developing the answer, connect this to ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to financial literacy. A reader would also benefit from understanding the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to financial literacy. The response should make room for how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to financial literacy. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. As part of the explanation, address how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to financial literacy. Please emphasize clarity, accuracy, and balanced reasoning throughout the response.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 306, 626, 1811, 304, 2274, 18161, 4631, 4135, 515, 278, 18520, 310, 263, 24452, 18987, 3239, 5925, 363, 385, 3641, 4983, 4274, 29889, 3529, 15544, 278, 11261, 297, 263, 982, 393, 338, 16232, 29892, 15579, 29892, 322, 5407, 363, 10608, 3907, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 15839, 2693, 1860, 393, 1754, 278, 2228, 901, 4100, 975, 931, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 8561, 2821, 607, 5633, 310, 278, 2228, 526, 16021, 29892, 607, 526, 17407, 29892, 322, 607, 526, 11314, 936, 29889, 3115, 3160, 263, 10679, 310, 278, 6297, 310, 1737, 5275, 29892, 22035, 12425, 29892, 322, 2130, 304, 7788, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 278, 1472, 29899, 8489, 27721, 393, 1122, 367, 22622, 304, 14111, 7389, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 319, 5407, 1234, 881, 4612, 278, 11302, 22450, 1546, 6210, 29892, 6534, 2264, 29892, 21750, 3097, 29892, 322, 1472, 29899, 8489, 1411, 3097, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 20355, 915, 920, 278, 11261, 4511, 29879, 304, 1432, 3250, 2834, 408, 1532, 408, 7200, 5264, 6757, 29889, 450, 8252, 881, 451, 11455, 278, 4328, 1546, 5557, 291, 29892, 28206, 29892, 322, 1380, 335, 362, 16650, 583, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 3529, 884, 25917, 920, 304, 20820, 17924, 1136, 8841, 515, 1722, 27836, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 29889, 7280, 4100, 10696, 338, 920, 25812, 881, 367, 16459, 746, 10757, 338, 28907, 297, 8220, 304, 18161, 4631, 4135, 298