e management. The explanation should not ignore a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to waste management. Please also examine the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to waste management. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. A balanced response should mention a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to waste management. For practical context, discuss how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to waste management. To avoid oversimplifying, include how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to waste management. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. A reader would also benefit from understanding a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to waste management. The response should make room for how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to waste management. Where appropriate, include how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to waste management. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. Also include a discussion of which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to waste management. In addition, consider what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to waste management. A useful answer should cover how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to waste management. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. The explanation should not ignore what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to waste management. Please also examine the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to waste management.