INFO 05-05 17:37:58 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-90fc2c69e05646b58548a0ff6b0a3e47-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about human memory for a community organizer preparing a public workshop. Please interpret the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. Please also examine a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to human memory. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. A balanced response should mention how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to human memory. For practical context, discuss a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to human memory. To avoid oversimplifying, include the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to human memory. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. A reader would also benefit from understanding the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to human memory. The response should make room for how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to human memory. Where appropriate, include the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to human memory. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. Also include a discussion of the main causes that created the current situation in relation to human memory. In addition, consider how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to human memory. A useful answer should cover what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to human memory. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. The explanation should not ignore the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to human memory. Please also examine the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to human memory. Another important angle is how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to human memory. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. For practical context, discuss how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to human memory. To avoid oversimplifying, include a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to human memory. When developing the answer, connect this to what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to human memory. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. The response should make room for what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to human memory. Where appropriate, include how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to human memory. As part of the explanation, address the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to human memory. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. In addition, consider one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to human memory. A useful answer should cover the most realistic solutions available today in relation to human memory. To make the response more complete, include ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to human memory. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. Please also examine how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to human memory. Another important angle is how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to human memory. A balanced response should mention how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to human memory. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. To avoid oversimplifying, include which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to human memory. When developing the answer, connect this to how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to human memory. A reader would also benefit from understanding the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to human memory. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. Where appropriate, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to human memory. As part of the explanation, address the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to human memory. Also include a discussion of how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to human memory. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. A useful answer should cover which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to human memory. To make the response more complete, include an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to human memory. The explanation should not ignore the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to human memory. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. Another important angle is the short-term effects people notice first in relation to human memory. A balanced response should mention why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to human memory. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 1954, 22094, 366, 526, 10223, 292, 263, 2821, 28976, 1234, 1048, 5199, 3370, 363, 263, 7881, 2894, 3950, 10223, 292, 263, 970, 664, 19032, 29889, 3529, 6613, 278, 6964, 29892, 2020, 372, 13750, 29892, 322, 920, 2305, 881, 1348, 1048, 967, 15031, 2411, 5795, 29889, 3529, 884, 25917, 263, 10230, 1546, 1023, 1422, 13501, 304, 278, 1021, 18766, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 6652, 6202, 728, 1546, 3273, 29899, 8489, 15031, 537, 322, 1472, 29899, 8489, 15075, 475, 3097, 29889, 319, 6411, 8362, 2933, 881, 3585, 920, 278, 11261, 1795, 1106, 1422, 297, 17173, 29891, 322, 4482, 29899, 10314, 6055, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 1152, 15031, 3030, 29892, 5353, 263, 1855, 29899, 11526, 3483, 6933, 393, 947, 451, 288, 874, 13699, 1598, 278, 2228, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 1763, 4772, 288, 874, 13699, 9215, 29892, 3160, 278, 3957, 1546, 5375, 19995, 322, 7200, 1788, 29899, 5563, 714, 26807, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 512, 2325, 3307, 3030, 577, 278, 1234, 3732, 4060, 304, 4856, 11735, 292, 278, 11261, 363, 278, 937, 931, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 278, 4328, 1546, 5557, 291, 29892, 28206, 29892, 322, 1380, 335, 362, 16650, 583, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 920, 278, 11261, 1033, 6602, 2305, 17587, 8679, 373, 5046, 29892, 17869, 29892, 4423, 29892, 470, 9793, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 4328, 1546, 825, 5925, 414, 1073, 322, 825, 13665, 962, 21079, 508, 2334, 297, 8220, 304, 5199, 3370, 29889, 19152, 278