INFO 05-05 17:38:50 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-be91b4f046dc4cafbfb5df7a1428e024-0: prompt: 'Imagine you are preparing a clear educational answer about sports science for a journalist planning background research for an explainer article. Please clarify the concept, why it matters, and how people should think about its practical implications. When developing the answer, connect this to how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to sports science. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. The response should make room for how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to sports science. Where appropriate, include how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to sports science. As part of the explanation, address why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to sports science. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. In addition, consider how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to sports science. A useful answer should cover which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to sports science. To make the response more complete, include an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to sports science. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. Please also examine how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to sports science. Another important angle is the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to sports science. A balanced response should mention a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to sports science. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. To avoid oversimplifying, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to sports science. When developing the answer, connect this to what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to sports science. A reader would also benefit from understanding the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to sports science. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. Where appropriate, include what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to sports science. As part of the explanation, address how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to sports science. Also include a discussion of what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to sports science. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. A useful answer should cover the main causes that created the current situation in relation to sports science. To make the response more complete, include the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to sports science. The explanation should not ignore how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to sports science. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. Another important angle is a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to sports science. A balanced response should mention the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to sports science. For practical context, discuss how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to sports science. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. When developing the answer, connect this to the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to sports science. A reader would also benefit from understanding one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to sports science. The response should make room for the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to sports science. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. As part of the explanation, address ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to sports science. Also include a discussion of how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to sports science. In addition, consider a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to sports science. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. To make the response more complete, include how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to sports science. The explanation should not ignore how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to sports science. Please also examine the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to sports science. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. A balanced response should mention the most realistic solutions available today in relation to sports science. For practical context, discuss the short-term effects people notice first in relation to sports science. To avoid oversimplifying, include what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to sports science. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to sports science. The response should make room for the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to sports science. The final response should help a reader understand the issue well enough to ask better follow-up questions.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 1954, 22094, 366, 526, 10223, 292, 263, 2821, 28976, 1234, 1048, 14717, 10466, 363, 263, 24452, 18987, 3239, 5925, 363, 385, 3641, 4983, 4274, 29889, 3529, 15544, 278, 6964, 29892, 2020, 372, 13750, 29892, 322, 920, 2305, 881, 1348, 1048, 967, 15031, 2411, 5795, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 920, 2024, 19995, 16254, 411, 970, 22035, 12425, 297, 8220, 304, 14717, 10466, 29889, 1938, 451, 5251, 278, 9591, 2307, 9906, 278, 16905, 7931, 370, 352, 653, 29889, 450, 2933, 881, 1207, 5716, 363, 920, 304, 5649, 278, 11261, 1728, 337, 5890, 373, 432, 1191, 265, 297, 8220, 304, 14717, 10466, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 920, 278, 11261, 1033, 6602, 2305, 17587, 8679, 373, 5046, 29892, 17869, 29892, 4423, 29892, 470, 9793, 297, 8220, 304, 14717, 10466, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 2020, 970, 9311, 13750, 746, 2902, 1372, 23120, 1048, 278, 11261, 297, 8220, 304, 14717, 10466, 29889, 319, 5405, 3907, 278, 2933, 8839, 373, 1857, 9763, 4959, 6521, 278, 6964, 6858, 372, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 920, 304, 20820, 17924, 1136, 8841, 515, 1722, 27836, 297, 8220, 304, 14717, 10466, 29889, 319, 5407, 1234, 881, 4612, 607, 6851, 526, 2504, 5921, 541, 1603, 9078, 491, 3438, 29892, 6287, 29892, 470, 12536, 3097, 297, 8220, 304, 14717, 10466, 29889, 1763, 1207, 278, 2933, 901, 4866, 29892, 3160, 385, 1342, 310, 263, 3619, 3984, 535, 1441, 322, 2020, 372, 338, 3984, 25369, 2