INFO 05-05 17:39:42 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-139bfa76a0214feb82956d71744ddd65-0: prompt: 'Provide a thoughtful explanation of biodiversity for a high school student preparing for a class discussion. The goal is not just to define the term, but to show how the topic works in real situations. In addition, consider what information would be most important in a short presentation in relation to biodiversity. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. To make the response more complete, include the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to biodiversity. The explanation should not ignore how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to biodiversity. Please also examine how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to biodiversity. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. A balanced response should mention a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to biodiversity. For practical context, discuss how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to biodiversity. To avoid oversimplifying, include the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to biodiversity. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. A reader would also benefit from understanding the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to biodiversity. The response should make room for the risks of ignoring the issue until it becomes more expensive to address in relation to biodiversity. Where appropriate, include the most realistic solutions available today in relation to biodiversity. Mention important uncertainties or limitations without making the response vague. Also include a discussion of how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to biodiversity. In addition, consider how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to biodiversity. A useful answer should cover how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to biodiversity. Make the response useful for someone who needs both background knowledge and practical judgment. The explanation should not ignore how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to biodiversity. Please also examine how to avoid making the answer sound more certain than the evidence supports in relation to biodiversity. Another important angle is the ways local conditions can change what counts as a good solution in relation to biodiversity. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. For practical context, discuss the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to biodiversity. To avoid oversimplifying, include the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to biodiversity. When developing the answer, connect this to a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to biodiversity. Suggest useful questions for further study at the end of the response. The response should make room for an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to biodiversity. Where appropriate, include the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to biodiversity. As part of the explanation, address ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to biodiversity. If multiple viewpoints exist, represent the strongest version of each before evaluating them. In addition, consider a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to biodiversity. A useful answer should cover a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to biodiversity. To make the response more complete, include how to distinguish expert consensus from open debate in relation to biodiversity. Use a clear structure with an introduction, several connected paragraphs, and a brief conclusion. Please also examine an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to biodiversity. Another important angle is the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to biodiversity. A balanced response should mention how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to biodiversity. Use concrete language whenever possible, but do not sacrifice accuracy. To avoid oversimplifying, include the main causes that created the current situation in relation to biodiversity. When developing the answer, connect this to the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to biodiversity. A reader would also benefit from understanding which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to biodiversity. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. Where appropriate, include what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to biodiversity. As part of the explanation, address what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to biodiversity. Also include a discussion of the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to biodiversity. Use examples carefully and explain why each example supports the broader point. A useful answer should cover how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to biodiversity. To make the response more complete, include why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to biodiversity. The explanation should not ignore a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to biodiversity. Keep the tone neutral, informative, and appropriate for an academic discussion. Avoid unsupported claims and make the reasoning easy to follow.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 9133, 680, 263, 2714, 1319, 8252, 310, 289, 2660, 24974, 363, 263, 1880, 3762, 8368, 10223, 292, 363, 263, 770, 10679, 29889, 450, 7306, 338, 451, 925, 304, 4529, 278, 1840, 29892, 541, 304, 1510, 920, 278, 11261, 1736, 297, 1855, 18845, 29889, 512, 6124, 29892, 2050, 825, 2472, 723, 367, 1556, 4100, 297, 263, 3273, 24329, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 12027, 7420, 825, 10757, 723, 1371, 4856, 16833, 3692, 263, 5995, 338, 4549, 470, 8062, 29889, 1763, 1207, 278, 2933, 901, 4866, 29892, 3160, 278, 297, 1760, 3145, 393, 8267, 920, 2305, 322, 21561, 23389, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 450, 8252, 881, 451, 11455, 920, 2551, 1033, 367, 17005, 773, 15031, 4221, 4097, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 3529, 884, 25917, 920, 278, 9545, 1163, 4822, 23507, 29892, 12786, 29892, 470, 17869, 6471, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 8984, 714, 738, 3619, 3984, 535, 1441, 29879, 393, 1033, 3275, 304, 6460, 1602, 12112, 29889, 319, 6411, 8362, 2933, 881, 3585, 263, 10483, 6445, 920, 278, 11261, 1795, 4383, 297, 278, 2446, 316, 6332, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 1152, 15031, 3030, 29892, 5353, 920, 278, 2228, 6602, 29879, 15311, 14218, 2834, 3265, 1135, 871, 2902, 1372, 297, 8220, 304, 289, 2660, 24974, 29889, 1763, 4772, 288, 874, 13699, 9215, 29892, 3160, 278, 20813, 2305, 4049, 1207, 746, 896, 937, 11735, 278, 11261, 297, 8220