INFO 05-05 17:40:45 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-9b6ec4a3e6384626a47a4a6567275270-0: prompt: 'I need a well-organized answer about neuroscience. Assume the reader is a journalist planning background research for an explainer article, and focus on clarity, examples, tradeoffs, and common misunderstandings. A balanced response should mention how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to neuroscience. Avoid simply listing facts; explain how the ideas relate to each other. To avoid oversimplifying, include what kinds of institutions are most responsible for managing the issue in relation to neuroscience. When developing the answer, connect this to how the topic might look different in wealthy and low-resource settings in relation to neuroscience. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to neuroscience. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. Where appropriate, include the role of geography, infrastructure, and access to resources in relation to neuroscience. As part of the explanation, address a practical illustration of how data could be used responsibly in relation to neuroscience. Also include a discussion of one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to neuroscience. Include enough context so the answer makes sense to someone encountering the topic for the first time. A useful answer should cover a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to neuroscience. To make the response more complete, include the most realistic solutions available today in relation to neuroscience. The explanation should not ignore the difference between what researchers know and what policymakers can implement in relation to neuroscience. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. Another important angle is how the issue affects ordinary daily life rather than only experts in relation to neuroscience. A balanced response should mention how the effects differ across communities, regions, or income groups in relation to neuroscience. For practical context, discuss the incentives that shape how people and institutions behave in relation to neuroscience. End with the two or three most important takeaways a reader should remember. When developing the answer, connect this to what questions a skeptical audience would probably ask in relation to neuroscience. A reader would also benefit from understanding the assumptions people often make when they first encounter the topic in relation to neuroscience. The response should make room for how data quality can shape the reliability of conclusions in relation to neuroscience. Explain the difference between correlation, causation, and reasonable inference when relevant. As part of the explanation, address how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to neuroscience. Also include a discussion of the main causes that created the current situation in relation to neuroscience. In addition, consider the tradeoffs between speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to neuroscience. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. To make the response more complete, include how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to neuroscience. The explanation should not ignore the technical constraints that make simple solutions difficult in relation to neuroscience. Please also examine how to present both benefits and limitations fairly in relation to neuroscience. Where useful, compare individual actions with institutional or system-level changes. A balanced response should mention a comparison between two different approaches to the same challenge in relation to neuroscience. For practical context, discuss an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to neuroscience. To avoid oversimplifying, include the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to neuroscience. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. A reader would also benefit from understanding how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to neuroscience. The response should make room for a scenario showing how the topic might matter in the next decade in relation to neuroscience. Where appropriate, include the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to neuroscience. Distinguish between short-term practicality and long-term sustainability. Also include a discussion of what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to neuroscience. In addition, consider how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to neuroscience. A useful answer should cover the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to neuroscience. Do not write a checklist; produce a coherent explanatory answer. The explanation should not ignore which solutions are promising but still limited by cost, scale, or reliability in relation to neuroscience. Please also examine ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to neuroscience. Another important angle is the connection between individual choices and larger system-level outcomes in relation to neuroscience. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. For practical context, discuss how to make the explanation useful to someone who must make a decision in relation to neuroscience. To avoid oversimplifying, include the short-term effects people notice first in relation to neuroscience. When developing the answer, connect this to the environmental, social, and economic drivers behind the problem in relation to neuroscience. The answer should be useful as background for a classroom discussion or short written report.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=1024, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [1, 306, 817, 263, 1532, 29899, 6388, 1891, 1234, 1048, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 22680, 278, 9591, 338, 263, 24452, 18987, 3239, 5925, 363, 385, 3641, 4983, 4274, 29892, 322, 8569, 373, 7542, 537, 29892, 6455, 29892, 11302, 22450, 29892, 322, 3619, 19818, 1689, 886, 29889, 319, 6411, 8362, 2933, 881, 3585, 920, 10608, 2136, 414, 881, 7536, 277, 675, 8820, 746, 7788, 526, 9078, 297, 8220, 304, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 319, 5405, 3763, 18028, 17099, 29936, 5649, 920, 278, 7014, 29279, 304, 1269, 916, 29889, 1763, 4772, 288, 874, 13699, 9215, 29892, 3160, 825, 17690, 310, 21561, 526, 1556, 14040, 363, 767, 6751, 278, 2228, 297, 8220, 304, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 1932, 14338, 278, 1234, 29892, 4511, 445, 304, 920, 278, 11261, 1795, 1106, 1422, 297, 17173, 29891, 322, 4482, 29899, 10314, 6055, 297, 8220, 304, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 319, 9591, 723, 884, 14169, 515, 8004, 920, 304, 5649, 278, 11261, 1728, 337, 5890, 373, 432, 1191, 265, 297, 8220, 304, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 4803, 6455, 515, 901, 1135, 697, 3030, 565, 393, 6911, 1510, 2020, 278, 2228, 338, 12092, 29889, 6804, 8210, 29892, 3160, 278, 6297, 310, 1737, 5275, 29892, 22035, 12425, 29892, 322, 2130, 304, 7788, 297, 8220, 304, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 1094, 760, 310, 278, 8252, 29892, 3211, 263, 15031, 8632, 362, 310, 920, 848, 1033, 367, 1304, 5544, 14981, 297, 8220, 304, 17167, 1883, 15277, 29889, 3115, 3160, 263, 10679, 310, 697, 18387, 1342, 3