etween speed, fairness, affordability, and long-term durability in relation to green chemistry. For practical context, discuss the difference between prevention, adaptation, and mitigation strategies in relation to green chemistry. To avoid oversimplifying, include the role of technology compared with education, policy, and behavior change in relation to green chemistry. Explain what evidence would help someone judge whether a claim is strong or weak. A reader would also benefit from understanding how to explain the topic without relying on jargon in relation to green chemistry. The response should make room for how uncertainty should be handled when evidence is incomplete in relation to green chemistry. Where appropriate, include what an effective first step would look like for a small community in relation to green chemistry. Do not assume the reader already knows the technical vocabulary. Also include a discussion of why public trust matters when experts communicate about the topic in relation to green chemistry. In addition, consider one concrete example that makes the concept easier to understand in relation to green chemistry. A useful answer should cover the long-term consequences that may be harder to observe immediately in relation to green chemistry. Make clear which parts of the issue are scientific, which are economic, and which are ethical. The explanation should not ignore how the topic could affect people differently depending on age, income, location, or education in relation to green chemistry. Please also examine a case where good intentions can produce weak results in relation to green chemistry. Another important angle is the historical developments that made the issue more important over time in relation to green chemistry. Describe how the topic connects to everyday life as well as larger social systems. For practical context, discuss how decision makers should prioritize actions when resources are limited in relation to green chemistry. To avoid oversimplifying, include what a beginner is most likely to misunderstand at first in relation to green chemistry. When developing the answer, connect this to the unintended consequences that can appear when a solution is poorly designed in relation to green chemistry. When there are tradeoffs, describe who benefits, who pays the cost, and why the balance is difficult. The response should make room for ethical questions that appear once the topic is applied in practice in relation to green chemistry. Where appropriate, include which terms should be defined before discussing the details in relation to green chemistry. As part of the explanation, address how costs and benefits may change as the solution is scaled up in relation to green chemistry. Point out any common misconceptions that could lead to poor decisions. In addition, consider the short-term effects people notice first in relation to green chemistry. A useful answer should cover an example of a common misconception and why it is misleading in relation to green chemistry. To make the response more complete, include how private choices interact with public infrastructure in relation to green chemistry. Use examples from more than one context if that helps show why the issue is complicated. Please also examine the main causes that created the current situation in relation to green chemistry. Another important angle is a real-world analogy that does not oversimplify the issue in relation to green chemistry. A balanced response should mention an example that connects the topic to science, economics, and public policy in relation to green chemistry. Avoid making the response depend on current news events unless the concept requires it. To avoid oversimplifying, include how success could be measured using practical indicators in relation to green chemistry. Please emphasize clarity, accuracy, and balanced reasoning throughout the response.', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.